00:56:42.784 --> 00:56:44.200
ERIN SODERBERG:
Thank you, Cedric.

00:56:44.200 --> 00:56:47.510
I think we have time for
one question, maybe two.

00:56:47.510 --> 00:56:50.510
AUDIENCE: So some of us here are
software engineers, not quite

00:56:50.510 --> 00:56:51.660
the number 1 profession.

00:56:51.660 --> 00:56:53.490
But we're OK on the list.

00:56:53.490 --> 00:56:57.900
And when we write
180-page program,

00:56:57.900 --> 00:57:00.110
we're pretty sure there's
some problems in it,

00:57:00.110 --> 00:57:03.164
and we have some
tools for fixing that.

00:57:03.164 --> 00:57:04.580
How does that
compare to the tours

00:57:04.580 --> 00:57:07.526
you have to make sure
your 180 pages are right?

00:57:10.360 --> 00:57:12.110
CEDRIC VILLANI: It's
pretty much the same.

00:57:12.110 --> 00:57:14.280
We know there are
always mistakes.

00:57:14.280 --> 00:57:18.800
And big problem is to
understand it sufficiently well

00:57:18.800 --> 00:57:21.350
that you are confident
it will work,

00:57:21.350 --> 00:57:24.780
even if there are
these small mistakes.

00:57:24.780 --> 00:57:27.150
From time to time, you fail.

00:57:27.150 --> 00:57:28.880
And there are famous
cases in which

00:57:28.880 --> 00:57:32.780
a famous theorem, for instance,
becomes a conjecture when

00:57:32.780 --> 00:57:35.310
the big mistake is discovered.

00:57:35.310 --> 00:57:37.860
And there are some--
in the history

00:57:37.860 --> 00:57:39.360
of 20th-century
mathematics, there

00:57:39.360 --> 00:57:42.240
are some famous cases like this,
in particular, for some reason,

00:57:42.240 --> 00:57:44.720
in the field of
dynamical systems.

00:57:44.720 --> 00:57:52.510
And so we are never really sure
if some important criteria is

00:57:52.510 --> 00:57:56.400
later, when someone simplifies
a proof, when someone gets

00:57:56.400 --> 00:58:00.440
a different proof of the same
result, when the theorem is

00:58:00.440 --> 00:58:04.530
taught, when you get lectures,
et cetera and so forth.

00:58:04.530 --> 00:58:09.040
But it's so difficult to
take the mistakes out.

00:58:09.040 --> 00:58:12.320
So right now, there
is all this trend

00:58:12.320 --> 00:58:18.480
about automatic checking of
proofs, with, in particular,

00:58:18.480 --> 00:58:21.560
research institutions like
[INAUDIBLE] in France.

00:58:21.560 --> 00:58:24.080
And for instance, one
of the leaders in this,

00:58:24.080 --> 00:58:30.190
Georges recently worked
out this challenge.

00:58:30.190 --> 00:58:33.560
He took a famous
proof in group theory,

00:58:33.560 --> 00:58:36.530
I think like a 200-page
proof, a big thing,

00:58:36.530 --> 00:58:40.280
and-or translated it
in this Coq language,

00:58:40.280 --> 00:58:44.320
which supports
automatic verification.

00:58:44.320 --> 00:58:46.980
And showed, indeed, that
even though in the proof

00:58:46.980 --> 00:58:52.040
there were some minor mistakes,
the whole thing was correct.

00:58:52.040 --> 00:58:56.810
Certainly this will
develop and develop.

00:58:56.810 --> 00:59:00.370
In the same group--
because, of course,

00:59:00.370 --> 00:59:04.830
it's a mixture of logic,
computer science, mathematics,

00:59:04.830 --> 00:59:08.740
and so on-- in the same
group there is Xavier Leroy..

00:59:08.740 --> 00:59:09.920
Some of you may know him.

00:59:09.920 --> 00:59:10.810
Yes.

00:59:10.810 --> 00:59:14.210
So he worked on the
certified C compiler,

00:59:14.210 --> 00:59:18.060
and he explains every
single of the C compilers

00:59:18.060 --> 00:59:19.790
which are out there
has some bugs.

00:59:19.790 --> 00:59:23.140
A bug meaning that sometimes
you do the program,

00:59:23.140 --> 00:59:25.690
and the executive
file resulting from it

00:59:25.690 --> 00:59:28.370
is not the one
that you would want

00:59:28.370 --> 00:59:30.870
and in some locations
gives the wrong answer.

00:59:30.870 --> 00:59:33.040
Except his one,
which he developed

00:59:33.040 --> 00:59:35.860
specifically using
this machinery

00:59:35.860 --> 00:59:37.880
of automatic checking.

00:59:37.880 --> 00:59:43.040
So I think it's quite
the same problem.

00:59:43.040 --> 00:59:48.590
With long computer softwares
and long mathematical proofs,

00:59:48.590 --> 00:59:53.600
there are always bugs in there,
except if you can, as you said,

00:59:53.600 --> 00:59:56.449
check them specifically
and systematically.

00:59:56.449 --> 00:59:58.240
ERIN SODERBERG: I thank
